<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Goldsmith and Lester</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">VEP 0039</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><a name="_Toc358302911"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written Submission by Professor Julian Roberts and Professor Mike Hough (VEP 0039)</span></a></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:62.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:373.95pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Do you think sentence length is a valid proxy for deciding which prisoners get the right to vote?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It is the best proxy for offence seriousness, and is preferable to a scheme which excludes certain prisoners, i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> those convicted of personal injury offences. Yet sentence length is still a poor tool to distinguish between prisoners in order to determine who should be disenfranchised. There is no point on the dimension of sentence length which provides a cut</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">off which is anything but arbitrary. The few correctional regimes that use sentence length – such as Canada – did so drawing upon an important</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> division of jurisdiction. Thus in Canada, federal prisoners – those serving two years or longer were disenfranchised, while provincial prisoners retained the vote. The federal provincial correctional bifurcation in jurisdiction split in Canada was important but has no </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">equivalent </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">counterpart in England and Wales. (In addition the disenfranchisement of federal prisoners </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">in Canada </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">was ultimately struck down on constitutional grounds</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in R. v. Sauve)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. The closest alternative </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">in England </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">would be the Magistrate/ Crown court division but using this as the division would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">in our view </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">be overbroad: federal prisoners in Canada represented only </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">approximately </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">3% of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">total Canadian </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">prison population; prisoners sentenced from the Crown Court represent a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">significantly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> higher percentage of the total prisoner population.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> If not, what would be your preferred approach?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Our preferred approach would involve </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">two </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">steps:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:39.8pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Create a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">statutory </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">schedule of offences for which disenfranchisement would be an option for the sentencing court</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">his list would include offences involving </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">specific </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">acts against the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">electoral process or the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">state</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> more generally (e.g.,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> electoral fraud</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. Consideration may be given to a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">dual element regime: some </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">combination of (a) crime against the state, (b) seriousness enough to justify a sentence of custody in excess of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">some threshold</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Thus if a court was sentencing someone for a listed offence, and was imposing a term </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">above this threshold</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, it would have the power to disenfranchise the prisoner for the custodial portion of the sentence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:39.8pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Direct the Sentencing Council to devise guidance on the principles to follow when deciding whether to disenfranchise the offender.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">What, if anything, is the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">significance of four</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> years and/or six months in the sentencing of criminals? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">As noted, there is no significance; both are arbitrary thresholds.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If you were to draw a line between serious and non-serious offences using sentence length, where would it be?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We would not draw the line, but one possibility would be to disenfranchise anyone sentenced to life imprisonment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> on the grounds that they have committed a crime of such seriousness that the most severe penalty was warranted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Can you think of an example where the sentence length approach could lead to an anomalous result? (For example, electoral fraud may result in a short sentence.)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Many cases heard at the Crown Court involve several counts, some relating to the same incident, some relating to completely separate incidents. If a threshold relating to sentence length is applied clear rules will be needed about the way in which total sentence is calculated. Clearly it would be anomalous to sum concurrent sentences, but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">more </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rational to do so for consecutive ones</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It has been suggested by Liberty that the disenfranchisement of prisoners disproportionately impacts on ethnic minority communities. Is this correct?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Any groups that are less likely than others to secure sentencing discounts – eg for early guilty pleas or for expressing remorse will – other things being equal – be more likely to be disenfranchised. There is evidence that BME groups are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">less likely</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to enter early guilty pleas.</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Can you provide further details of the types of people that might be over-represented in those sentenced to a) more than six months and b) more than four years? </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">People nearing the end of their criminal careers – aiming to find a route out of crime – may by virtue of their long record actually be sentenced more heavily than those who are not trying to stop. This group may be over-represented.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">According to a note from the House of Commons Library,</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">approximately a quarter of those sentenced to less than four years have been convicted of a violent or sexual offence.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Under what circumstances would someone convicted of these types of offences be sentenced to less than four years?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">As noted, we are of the view that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">category-based exclusions are unwise. Why would you want to disenfranchise someone convicted of a crime of violence against a single individual </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">but</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> not someone who has deprived dozens of elderly victims of their life savings </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">yet</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> who is convicted of a property crime? Crime seriousness is a better yardstick</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> than offence category</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, but as we noted, there is no non-arbitrary cut</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">off. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">But to address the question directly, many offenders convicted of a crime of violence would be sentenced to much less than 4 years. For example, the guideline range for common assault carries a ceiling of 26 weeks.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Section 47 assaults are divided in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">definitive sentencing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">guideline into 3 categories of seriousness, each with its own sentence range. The sentence range for the most serious category (1) is from 1-3 years.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> The guidelines for less serious sexual assault involving an adult victim has starting points that span the custody threshold.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">What proportion of convictions results in a custodial sentence?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">8% (98,047) of all offenders sentenced in 2012  (n = 1,229,827) get a custodial sen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">tence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. This includes motoring and summary offences.</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> What proportion of those convicted of criminal offences receive sentences of 4 years or more,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or of 6 months or more?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">55,777</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> got a custodial sentence of 6 months or less (ie 4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">%</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> of 1.2m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">89,289</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> got a custodial sentence of under four years (ie just over 7%)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">8,758</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> got four years or more (or indeterminate)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> – ie 0.7%</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Of the, 1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,229,827 sentenced in 2012, 1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,139,263 are sentenced in magistrates courts and 90,564 are sentenced in the Crown Court (ie 7%)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Can you tell us what proportion of those individuals convicted in the magistrates’ court will be subsequently committed for sentence in the Crown Court?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">19,754 offenders out of the 1,160,776 offenders found guilty at magistrates courts are committed for sentence. (not quite 2%)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">How many persons, convicted in the magistrates’ court of multiple offences, are given custodial sentences of more than six months in prison?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">810 of the 1,132,866 offenders </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">for whom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> sentence length data </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">are available </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">in magistrates</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> courts </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">we</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">re given sentences over 6 months.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For those convicted in the Crown Court, what proportion are given </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span s